To generate synthetic data for laser-accelerated ion beam with the given features, I will follow these steps:

1. Select target\_material from a list of possible materials (e.g., aluminium, gold, polypropylene, plastic).
2. Choose target\_thickness within realistic ranges based on the univariate statistics provided, considering that the data is not normally distributed and might have outliers or skewness. I will generate a random value between 0 and 125 microns with more samples closer to lower values as suggested by percentiles Q10 (0.273), Q25 (0.482), median (0.593) and Q75 (0.769).
3. Determine pulse\_width using the correlation between energy and pulse width, considering that there might be a non-linear relationship between these features due to different laser systems and experimental conditions. I will generate a random value between 24 fs and 12.9 ps with more samples closer to lower values as suggested by percentiles Q10 (30), Q25 (30) and median (30).
4. Adjust spot\_size within realistic ranges based on the univariate statistics provided, considering that this feature might have a high correlation with other features such as intensity and power. I will generate a random value between 2.13 um and 60 um with more samples closer to lower values as suggested by percentiles Q10 (3.3), Q25 (3.3) and median (3.3).
5. Calculate energy based on the formula E = I \* A, where I is intensity and A is spot size. This relationship assumes that the laser beam has a Gaussian profile and follows the laws of optics. I will generate random values for intensity between 1.05e+18 W/cm2 and 5.59e+21 W/cm2 based on percentiles Q10 (4.53e+19), Q25 (6.83e+19) and median (6.22e+20).
6. Calculate power using the formula P = E / pulse\_width, where E is energy and pulse\_width is the duration of the laser pulse in seconds. This relationship assumes that the laser has a constant peak power during its operation. I will generate random values for power between 1.76e+11 W and 3.83e+14 W based on percentiles Q10 (5.59e+12), Q25 (8.45e+12) and median (7.68e+13).
7. Calculate cutoff\_energy using the formula E\_cut = sqrt(I \* A), where I is intensity, A is spot size and E\_cut is the maximum energy that can be achieved by a particle accelerated by the laser pulse. This relationship assumes that the particles are accelerated in vacuum and follows the laws of physics. I will generate random values for cutoff\_energy between 3.3 MeV and 95 MeV based on percentiles Q10 (4.0), Q25 (4.4) and median (4.8).
